<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-07</title>

<p>This week brought an inflection point for unified Physical AI. NVIDIA shipped <b>Cosmos 3</b>, an open omnimodal world model that genuinely unifies language, image, video, audio, and action inside a single training framework — and released the code, weights, and synthetic datasets to back it. Alongside it, <b>Qwen-VLA</b> pitched a unified generalist VLA with a clever text-to-action pretraining recipe, but arrived with no code and a credibility crack we could measure: the headline +10.2 pp T2A ablation is not compute-matched. <b>GRAIL</b> demonstrated that synthetic humanoid data pipelines can now reach real-world deployment, producing 22,189 motions and validating them on a Unitree G1, though the reconstruction objective is dominated by a single contact loss with weight 1e5.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> Cosmos 3 is the clearest seed for the next generation of Physical AI foundation models. Its Mixture-of-Transformers architecture and domain-aware action representation are genuine contributions, and the open release makes them immediately buildable. The "unified Physical AI" claim is slightly overstated — headline results come from post-trained specialists — but the base model is still the strongest public starting point.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Unified Models for Physical AI</h1>

<p>The central tension this week is between <i>architectural unification</i> and <i>capability unification</i>. Two papers claim to collapse fragmented embodied-AI pipelines into single models. One delivers with open artifacts; the other promises much but ships a README and an ablation that conflates method with extra training.</p>

