<h2>GRAIL: Generating Humanoid Loco-Manipulation from 3D Assets and Video Priors</h2>
<p>NVIDIA + UCLA · 2606.05160 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.05160">HF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/NVlabs/GRAIL">GitHub</a></p>

<p>GRAIL's core insight is architectural, not algorithmic: instead of reconstructing an unconstrained in-the-wild video into an ambiguous 4D scene, <i>specify the 3D scene first</i> — object mesh, camera parameters, metric scale, environment depth, and a robot-proportioned character — then generate a human interaction video from that specification, and recover 4D human-object interaction inside the known metric frame.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:grail:pipeline]]</p>

<p>We ran actual checks against the released code, configs, and HuggingFace dataset. The findings are more nuanced than the prose suggests.</p>

<p><b>The reconstruction objective is dominated by one loss term.</b> Parsing <code>configs/recon_4dhoi/pickup_smplx.yaml</code> shows three stages (400 + 1000 + 400 = 1,800 iterations). The relative weight dominance is extreme:</p>

<pre lang="text" caption="Loss weight dominance in GRAIL pickup config"><code>human_traj_opt          : human_global_init_reg = 94.6% of total |weight|
human_global_traj_opt   : contact               = 99.7%
obj_traj_opt            : contact               = 99.5%</code></pre>

<p>The contact loss has weight <b>1e5</b> in stages 2 and 3. This is the only mechanism that snaps hands onto the object and keeps them there. Zeroing it would likely collapse reconstruction to a smooth hand motion that ignores the object. The <code>human_global_init_reg</code> term in stage 1 (weight 3e3) anchors the body to GENMO's global trajectory. These two terms are load-bearing; the rest are fine-tuning.</p>

<p><b>Undocumented behaviors in the loss terms.</b> We reimplemented the loss math from <code>grail/optimization/loss_terms.py</code> and ran synthetic unit tests:</p>

<ul>
  <li>The 20% outlier trimming in Chamfer distance can zero the depth loss entirely for small point clouds.</li>
  <li><code>smoothness_loss</code> penalizes first-order differences against zero, so even constant-velocity motion incurs loss.</li>
  <li>Contact loss is gated by 3D distance: if the closest hand-object distance exceeds <code>max_contact_dist</code>, the term is silently skipped. This is a stability feature when the VLM mislabels contact, but it is not mentioned in the paper.</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Released code is Docker-bound.</b> Importing <code>grail.optimization.loss_terms</code> directly fails with <code>ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'pytorch3d'</code>. The Docker pull timed out in our environment, so we could not run the full end-to-end pipeline. The practical reproducibility depends on the provided container.</p>

<p><b>Dataset count is 22,189, not 20,309.</b> We counted the released HuggingFace dataset by category. The paper's ">20,000" claim still holds, but the exact number is higher than previously reported. A real trajectory sample (<code>pickup_table__alcohol_0__000</code>) shows a 76 cm object lift, 31 cm root displacement, and hand-action toggles on every frame — physically plausible motion.</p>

<p><b>Real-world results are promising but thin.</b> GRAIL achieves 84% success on diverse object pick-up and 90% on stair-climbing with a Unitree G1, trained only on synthetic data. But trial counts are small (10 per object), the visual policy architecture is barely described, and there is no ablation isolating the data contribution from the SONIC pretrained controller or the sim-to-real pipeline.</p>

<p><b>Verdict: build on / track.</b> The privileged 3D setup is a genuine design pattern. The dataset and code make immediate follow-up work possible. The real-world numbers need more trials and baselines to be bulletproof, and the reconstruction objective is more brittle than it appears from the five-term equation in the paper.</p>

<h1>Cross-Cutting Observations</h1>

<p><b>The unification gap is widening.</b> All three deep-dived papers claim unification in some form — Cosmos 3 unifies modalities, Qwen-VLA unifies tasks and embodiments, GRAIL unifies generation and reconstruction. But in every case, the unified architecture is a starting point, and the headline capabilities come from downstream specialization. Cosmos 3's best T2I, I2V, and policy results are post-trained specialists. Qwen-VLA's RL stage is essentially a SimplerEnv specialist. GRAIL's real-world policy is a distilled specialist on top of a pretrained controller. This is not a criticism — it is the honest shape of the field.</p>

<p><b>Parameter costs matter.</b> Cosmos 3's MoT is a 1.85× parameter multiplier for the privilege of decoupled optimization. Qwen-VLA's domain-aware projections are negligible (~0.11% of backbone) but the T2A gain is confounded with extra training. GRAIL's reconstruction succeeds partly because a single loss term has weight 1e5. None of these facts invalidate the papers, but they show that the interesting claims live in engineering trade-offs, not magic.</p>

<p><b>Open release quality varies enormously.</b> Cosmos 3 and GRAIL ship code, weights, datasets, and configs. Qwen-VLA ships a README. When artifact completeness correlates with institutional backing (NVIDIA) rather than with paper impressiveness, the community has a reproducibility problem. The T2A pretraining insight in Qwen-VLA is genuinely interesting, but practitioners cannot adopt it without the artifacts.</p>

<p><b>Synthetic data is now a first-class citizen.</b> Cosmos 3 trains on five synthetic datasets. GRAIL generates 22,189 motions without a single teleoperation episode. The bottleneck is no longer data scarcity but <i>data quality</i> — all synthetic sources in Cosmos 3 degrade human video generation, and GRAIL's reconstruction relies on an extreme contact-loss weight to snap hands to objects. The next frontier is selective synthesis and domain-targeted refinement, not indiscriminate scaling.</p>
